<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
    ServiceNow Update Set record-definition for the `sys_dictionary` row that
    declares the `requester_name` String field on the `x_[scope]_case` custom
    table inside the scoped application `x_[scope]_case_management`.

    Per AAP Section 0.5.7 (Data-Model Mapping verbatim):
        Field            Type           Constraints
        requester_name   String(100)    Mandatory - captures external requester

    Per AAP Section 0.4.4 the case-submission portal page populates this field
    as one of the five user-supplied inputs:
        "Page 1 - Case Submission: a simple form with five inputs
        (subject, type, description, requester_name, requester_email)."
    The submission widget binds the requester-name text input to this field
    and passes its value through the scripted REST submission endpoint
    (../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml), which
    performs a GlideRecord.insert() against `x_[scope]_case` with the user-
    supplied requester-name literal.

    Per AAP Section 0.7.4 ("Portal lookup output filtering") this field is
    EXPLICITLY NOT exposed by the case-status-lookup endpoint - the lookup
    returns ONLY status, subject, opened_date - no internal fields exposed.
    requester_name is treated as INTERNAL because:
      (a) returning the requester's name to an arbitrary anonymous caller
          who happens to know a case number would leak personal-attribution
          information about who filed which case (e.g., enabling enumeration
          of which named individuals filed complaints);
      (b) AAP Section 0.7.4 enumerates exactly THREE whitelisted lookup
          fields, and requester_name is not among them.
    This intentional omission is enforced at the response-payload level by
    the lookup endpoint's CasePortalService.lookupCase() helper, which
    constructs a JSON object containing only the three permitted columns.

    Semantic source-side reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported):
      - acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java lines 47, 114,
        120, 389-427, 961-963: ArkCase did NOT carry a flat `requester_name`
        String column on `acm_case_file`. Instead, it modeled the external
        requester as a PersonAssociation with personType="Initiator",
        retrieved by getOriginator() / setOriginator() helpers that filter
        the case's PersonAssociation collection:

            public PersonAssociation getOriginator() {
                ...
                Optional<PersonAssociation> found = getPersonAssociations()
                    .stream()
                    .filter(pa -> "Initiator".equalsIgnoreCase(pa.getPersonType()))
                    .findFirst();
                ...
            }

        i.e., the requester was a row in `acm_person_assoc` (FK -> Person ->
        first_name + last_name across acm_person) joined back to the case via
        parent_id / parent_type. AAP Section 0.5.1 explicitly simplifies
        this for the POC: rather than requiring a synchronously-created
        PersonAssociation row at portal-submission time (which would couple
        the anonymous submission endpoint to two child-table inserts plus
        the optional `sys_user`/Person lookups they imply), the POC captures
        the requester's name as a free-form String directly on the case row.
        The richer requester-as-party model is still available via the
        x_[scope]_case_party table (AAP Section 0.5.7), where staff users
        can attach a typed Person or Organization party (with role_label
        such as "Requester") to a case AFTER initial submission.
      - The field name is `requester_name` (snake_case, 14 chars; NOT
        `requesterName`, NOT `originator`, NOT `initiator`, NOT
        `requester_full_name`) per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. Snake_case
        aligns with ServiceNow's platform-native column-naming convention
        (sys_user.first_name, sys_user.last_name, incident.opened_by, etc.)
        and matches the snake_case used by every other field on this
        scoped table (assigned_group, assigned_agent, opened_date,
        closed_date, requester_email).
      - ArkCase's ROOT-LEVEL CaseFile entity also exposes `getOriginator()`
        as part of the `AcmObjectOriginator` interface (CaseFile.java line
        120: implements ... AcmObjectOriginator). The POC's requester_name
        column does NOT implement that contract directly because the
        ServiceNow target abandons the cross-cutting Acm*Object interface
        family entirely (AAP Section 0.1.2 - Java domain classes become
        ServiceNow tables; cross-cutting interfaces are NOT replicated).

    Constraints honored (AAP Sections 0.7.1, 0.7.2, 0.7.4):
      - Scope-namespace exclusivity: `<name>` resolves to `x_[scope]_case`
        within the scoped application, and `<sys_scope>` / `<sys_package>`
        bind THIS dictionary record to the same scope by `source` attribute
        lookup. NO global-scope writes - the OOB tables `task`, `incident`,
        `sys_user`, `core_company`, etc. are never modified.
      - Zero hardcoded cross-reference sys_ids: the `<sys_scope>` and
        `<sys_package>` text-node values resolve by scope source name
        (`x_[scope]_case_management`), not by literal sys_id. The `<sys_id>`
        text-node value is THIS record's own deterministic primary key
        (MD5 of the canonical field identifier `x_[scope]_case.requester_name`)
        and is NOT a reference to any other record. The MD5 derivation
        guarantees that re-generation of this Update Set on any agent run
        produces a byte-identical `<sys_id>` (no random UUIDs), which is
        required for clean Update-Set re-import on a fresh PDI without
        creating duplicate sys_dictionary rows. Verified:
            python3 -c "import hashlib; print(hashlib.md5(b'x_[scope]_case.requester_name').hexdigest())"
        prints 696e73e041d826fe2d43a3f259acd1f1 (matches sys_id below).
      - The literal `[scope]` placeholder is preserved per AAP convention;
        the PDI auto-assigns the actual scope id at App Engine Studio
        creation time. The placeholder appears in `<name>`, `<sys_scope>`,
        `<sys_package>`, and `<sys_update_name>` consistently.
      - mandatory=true at the dictionary level (AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim:
        "requester_name | String(100) | Mandatory - captures external
        requester"). Without a requester name, the case has no external
        attribution and the case-submission portal page (AAP Section 0.4.4)
        cannot satisfy its specified contract that the requester provides
        a name. This MUST hold across all four insert paths into
        `x_[scope]_case`:
          (1) the internal form - the platform's form-layout engine renders
              an asterisk and refuses to save without a value;
          (2) the Table API (PUT/POST) - the platform returns a 400 with
              "field is mandatory" if missing;
          (3) the scripted REST submission endpoint - the endpoint's
              field-validation pre-check rejects an empty requester_name
              before invoking GlideRecord.insert() and returns a structured
              400 to the portal so the submission widget can display an
              inline error;
          (4) the seed-data scripts - all 10 demo cases populate this
              field with non-PII synthetic names (per AAP Section 0.7.2).
      - read_only=false: internal users with the case_manager role may
        correct an erroneous requester_name (e.g., a typo from the portal
        submission) AFTER the case is created; case_agent role users on
        assigned cases may also correct per AAP Section 0.5.6 ACL matrix.
        Internal-user write authorization is governed by the table-level
        ACLs in ../acl/ - this dictionary entry deliberately does NOT
        carry per-role write_roles since the table-level ACLs apply
        uniformly across all editable fields.
      - default_value is EMPTY (no implicit default) per AAP Section 0.5.7
        and the agent prompt's Phase 4 verbatim. Defaulting silently to a
        placeholder string ("Anonymous", "Unknown Requester", etc.) would
        silently mask submissions that failed mandatory enforcement and
        pollute the Manager View dashboard's per-requester drilldowns
        with semantically-empty rows. It would also undermine the synthetic-
        data audit trail: a row without a real synthetic name should fail
        validation, not coerce to a default.
      - audit=false per AAP Section 0.3.1 minimal-change clause and the
        agent prompt's Phase 4. The status field on this same table
        carries audit=true because every state transition must be
        reconstructable post-hoc; requester_name is descriptive identity
        metadata, not a regulated lifecycle attribute, so the additional
        sys_audit row per update is unnecessary overhead for a POC.
      - max_length=100 EXACTLY per AAP Section 0.5.7 verbatim. NOT 4000
        (description, the long-form free-text body), NOT 255 (subject, the
        case summary line), NOT 40 (number / type / status / priority,
        the controlled-vocabulary identifier-style strings). 100 chars
        comfortably accommodates international name forms with prefixes/
        suffixes (e.g., "Dr. Maria del Carmen Hernandez-Rodriguez, PhD"
        at 47 chars; "Sir Christopher Alexander Worthington III" at 41
        chars; CJK full names at 8-12 chars; transliterated forms at 30+
        chars), and matches the sibling requester_email column's 100-char
        ceiling for symmetric storage of the requester's two identity
        strings. Mirrors AAP Section 0.4.4's Page 1 - Case Submission
        sizing for the inline form input.
      - internal_type=string is correct for fields up to 4000 chars in
        ServiceNow. The platform's form engine renders a String column
        with max_length<=255 as a single-line text input (no `attributes`
        override required for this presentation), which matches the
        single-line name input expected on the portal submission form.
      - choice=0 = "Free-form String, no choice list" (NOT 3 like the
        type / status / priority fields). Names are unconstrained natural-
        language text; constraining them to a choice list would defeat
        the purpose of capturing a free-form external-requester name.
      - unique=false: multiple cases may legitimately share the same
        requester_name (e.g., a recurring requester who submits multiple
        cases over time, or two distinct individuals who happen to share
        a common name). Uniqueness at the case level is delegated entirely
        to the auto-generated `number` field per AAP Section 0.5.7
        (./x_[scope]_case_number.xml carries unique=true).
      - text_index=false per the agent prompt's Phase 6 verbatim. Unlike
        subject (text_index=true, the primary search target across the
        case list) and description (text_index=true, the long-form
        searchable body), requester_name is identity metadata that does
        not need to participate in the case-list quick-search index for
        the POC. Internal users wanting to filter by requester can still
        do so via the standard list-view condition builder (which works
        without a text index for short String columns at POC data
        volumes). Avoiding the index also reduces the surface area for
        accidental anonymous-list enumeration of requester names through
        any future search widget.
      - spell_check=false per the agent prompt's Phase 6 verbatim. Names
        are proper nouns and are not amenable to dictionary-based spell-
        checking - any spell-check suggestions on a name field generate
        false-positive squiggles that degrade UX without adding value.
        This matches the platform-native convention for sys_user.first_name
        and sys_user.last_name, which also disable spell_check.
      - attributes is EMPTY per the agent prompt's Phase 6 verbatim.
        Unlike description (attributes="edge_encryption_enabled=true",
        which marks the long-form narrative column eligible for ServiceNow
        Edge Encryption), the POC does NOT mark the requester_name column
        as Edge-Encryption-eligible. Edge Encryption support for short
        identity strings is intentionally out of POC scope; if a future
        production deployment requires it, the dictionary attribute can
        be added in a follow-up scoped change.
      - No reference target: this is a free-form String field, not a
        Reference field. All `<reference*>` elements are empty and
        `<table_reference>false</table_reference>`. The POC deliberately
        does NOT model requester_name as a Reference->sys_user because:
          (i) the case-submission portal is UNAUTHENTICATED (AAP Section
              0.4.4 - "two unauthenticated pages: case submission and
              case status lookup") - the anonymous submitter generally
              has no sys_user account and cannot be resolved to one;
          (ii) AAP Section 0.5.7's literal type for requester_name is
              "String(100)" - NOT a reference. The exact field type and
              constraint matrix is preserved verbatim per AAP Section
              0.7.1 ("Preserve the user-prompt's data-model field set
              verbatim - no additions, no renames, no type relaxations").
          (iii) The richer typed-party association (Person -> sys_user OR
              Organization -> core_company) is implemented separately on
              the x_[scope]_case_party child table, which staff users can
              populate AFTER initial submission to attach a Resolvable
              party with role_label such as "Requester".
      - No PII: per AAP Section 0.7.2 (No-PII constraint, "Synthetic data
        only. The seed users, groups, cases, tasks, and parties MUST be
        fabricated - no real names, real email addresses, real phone
        numbers, real organization names, or real case content.") and
        AAP Section 0.3.2 (synthetic-data-only constraint). NO real
        names from the source ArkCase database are placed in this column
        at any point in the build. Demo seed values are fabricated names
        such as "Demo Requester 01", "Demo Requester 02", "Synthetic
        Submitter Alpha", or "Test Requester Beta" - none of which are
        real individuals.

    Cross-references (AAP Section 0.5.2 dependency ordering):
      - This record MUST load AFTER `../tables/x_[scope]_case.xml`
        (parent table), since `<name>x_[scope]_case</name>` references
        the table by name.
      - This record MUST load BEFORE the consumers that read or write
        the `requester_name` column:
          * ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_submit.xml
            (the scripted REST submission endpoint - writes this field
            from the user's portal-form input on every anonymous case
            submission; AAP Section 0.4.4 lists `requester_name` as one
            of the five user-supplied inputs the page collects)
          * ../portal/widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_submission_widget.xml
            (the submission widget binds its requester-name text input
            to this field via the scripted REST submission endpoint)
          * ../script_includes/x_[scope]_CasePortalService.xml
            (the submitCase() helper method writes this field on behalf
            of the scripted REST submission endpoint)
          * ../seed-data/cases/x_[scope]_case_demo_*.xml (synthetic
            demo cases that MUST populate this mandatory field with
            synthetic non-PII names to satisfy AAP Section 0.7.4
            minimum-data threshold of "at least 10 cases across all
            statuses, both case types represented")

      - This record is EXPLICITLY NOT consumed by:
          * ../portal/rest/sys_ws_definition_x_[scope]_case_status_lookup.xml
            (the scripted REST status-lookup endpoint - per AAP Section
            0.7.4, the lookup returns ONLY status, subject, opened_date;
            requester_name is treated as internal/PII-protected and MUST
            NOT appear in the response payload). Implementations of the
            lookup endpoint MUST whitelist exactly status, subject,
            opened_date when constructing the response object - any
            leakage of requester_name is a portal-data-exposure violation
            per AAP Section 0.7.4.
          * ../portal/widgets/sp_widget_x_[scope]_case_lookup_widget.xml
            (consumes only the three whitelisted fields returned by the
            lookup endpoint).
-->
<record_update table="sys_dictionary">
    <sys_dictionary action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE">
